                            <comment id="13701210" author="cheolsoo" created="Sat, 6 Jul 2013 02:04:35 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;ReviewBoard:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://reviews.apache.org/r/12290/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://reviews.apache.org/r/12290/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13701651" author="cheolsoo" created="Sun, 7 Jul 2013 20:55:07 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Corrected few typos in a new patch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13703939" author="cheolsoo" created="Tue, 9 Jul 2013 23:47:36 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Rebased the patch to trunk. I also verified that all unit tests pass.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In terms of the fix, here is the summary of what I did.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When constructing antlr trees from case/in syntax, I used to collapse expressions into a flat list and assume that the first element is the lhs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i.e. expr IN ( expr, expr* ) -&amp;gt; ^( IN expr+ )&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But now I construct a list of sub-trees instead.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i.e. lhs IN ( rhs, rhs* ) -&amp;gt; ^( IN ^( LHS lhs ) ^( RHS rhs )+  )&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;This way it is clear where the boundaries between expressions are, so I no longer need to assume anything.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
